# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: webpack
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:webpack/build-automation] Build automation encompasses both sequencing build operations via non-interactive interface tools and running builds on a shared server.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Build automation tools allow sequencing the tasks of building software via a non-interactive interface.
[src:webpack/build-automation] A *build system* or *build automation tool* is a programming tool or set of tools that automate the compiling and linking of source code into an executable program or library.
[src:webpack/build-automation] They streamline the software development process by managing dependencies, resolving conflicts, and ensuring consistent builds across different environments.
[src:webpack/build-automation] When software projects grow complex, their build steps may involve multiple programming languages or compiling units, making manual build processes increasingly cumbersome.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Dependencies between code components necessitate careful ordering and potentially different tools for each piece.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Managing these dependencies manually can quickly lead to version conflicts, stale binaries, and difficulty tracking updates, making solutions such as shell scripts too difficult to maintain.
[src:webpack/build-automation] While individual developers might compile code directly, a robust build system is foundational to efficient software development in large organizations and teams, where automated builds become commonplace and most builds are triggered automatically rather than manually.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Given the essential role of build systems, it is said that they act as "repositories of essential build knowledge".
[src:webpack/build-automation] They effectively eliminate roadblocks and accelerate development velocity by enabling engineers to share resources and results.
[src:webpack/build-automation] An incremental build is a process within a build system where build tools use an incremental compiler to recompile only the parts of a software project that have changed since the last build, rather than rebuilding everything from scratch.
[src:webpack/build-automation] This optimization reduces build time by leveraging dependency tracking, caching, and selective compilation.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Incremental builds are especially valuable in large-scale software projects, where recompiling the entire codebase can be time-consuming and resource-intensive.
[src:webpack/build-automation] By identifying and compiling only the modified components—such as source files, libraries, or modules—the build system ensures faster iteration cycles, enabling developers to test and debug changes more efficiently.
[src:webpack/build-automation] The process relies on a dependency graph, which maps relationships between files, modules, or components in the project.
[src:webpack/build-automation] When a change is detected, the build system traverses this graph to determine which parts of the project are affected and need to be recompiled.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Modern build tools, such as Make, Gradle and Bazel, often incorporate incremental build capabilities to streamline development workflows.
[src:webpack/build-automation] While incremental builds offer significant performance advantages, they also introduce challenges, such as ensuring the accuracy of dependency tracking and avoiding stale or inconsistent build artifacts.
[src:webpack/build-automation] To address these issues, some build systems provide mechanisms for "clean builds," which rebuild the entire project from scratch to guarantee correctness when necessary.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Because of this issue, incremental builds are rarely used in continuous integration systems, where correctness is preferred to compilation speed.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Tools such as Make can be used via custom configuration file or using the command-line.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Custom tools such as shell scripts can also be used, although they become increasingly cumbersome as the codebase grows more complex.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Some tools, such as shell scripts, are task-oriented declarative programming.
[src:webpack/build-automation] They encode sequences of commands to perform with usually minimal conditional logic.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Some tools, such as Make are product-oriented.
[src:webpack/build-automation] They build a product, a.k.a. target, based on configured dependencies.
[src:webpack/build-automation] A build server is a server setup to run builds.
[src:webpack/build-automation] In contrast to a personal computer, a server allows for a more consistent and available build environment.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Traditionally, a build server was a local computer dedicated as a shared resource instead of used as a personal computer.
[src:webpack/build-automation] Today, there are many cloud computing, software as a service (SaaS) websites for building.
[src:webpack/build-automation] A continuous integration server is a build server that is setup to build in a relatively frequent way, often on each code commit.
[src:webpack/build-automation] A build server may also be incorporated into a tool for application release automation (ARA) or application lifecycle management (ALM).
[src:webpack/build-automation] Automating the build process is a required step for implementing continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD), all of which are considered best practices for software development.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] In this article, we provide an overview of modern web tooling, what kinds of tools are available and where you'll meet them in the lifecycle of web app development, and how to find help with individual tools.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Writing software for the web has become more sophisticated through the ages.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Although it is still entirely reasonable to write HTML, CSS, and JavaScript "by hand" there is now a wealth of tools that developers can use to speed up the process of building a website, or app.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] There are some extremely well-established tools that have become common "household names" amongst the development community, and new tools are being written and released every day to solve specific problems.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] You might even find yourself writing a piece of software to aid your own development process, to solve a specific problem that existing tools don't already seem to handle.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] It is easy to become overwhelmed by the sheer number of tools that can be included in a single project.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Equally, a single configuration file for a tool like webpack can be hundreds of lines long, most of which are magical incantations that seem to do the job but which only a master engineer will fully understand!
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] From time to time, even the most experienced of web developers get stuck on a tooling problem; it is possible to waste hours attempting to get a tooling pipeline working before even touching a single line of application code.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] If you have found yourself struggling in the past, then don't worry — you are not alone.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] In these articles, we won't answer every question about web tooling, but we will provide you with a useful starting point of understanding the fundamentals, which you can then build from.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] As with any complex topic, it is good to start small, and gradually work your way up to more advanced uses.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Today's modern developer tooling ecosystem is huge, so it's useful to have a broad idea of what main problems the tools are solving.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] If you jump on your favorite search engine and look for "front-end developer tools" you're going to hit a huge spectrum of results ranging from text editors, to browsers, to the type of pens you can use to take notes.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Though your choice of code editor is certainly a tooling choice, this series of articles will go beyond that, focusing on developer tools that help you produce web code more efficiently.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] We'll recommend a few particular tools and the following tutorials will show you how to use them.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] They are tools that are popular and standard at the time of writing.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] This does not preclude you from using other tools, if you are aware of their relative advantages.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Let's look at each one of these in more detail.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] The editor, operating system, and browser are all development environments.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] We will assume that you have already settled down with a choice you are most comfortable with.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] These are tools that make the code you write a little better.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] This part of the tooling should be specific to your own development environment, though it's not uncommon for companies to have some kind of policy or pre-baked configuration available to install so that all their developers are using the same processes.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] This includes anything that makes your development process easier for generating stable and reliable code.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Safety net tooling should also help you either prevent mistakes or correct mistakes automatically without having to build your code from scratch each time.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] A few very common safety net tool types you will find being used by developers are as follows.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] ESLint is the industry standard JavaScript linter — a highly configurable tool for catching potential syntax errors and encouraging "best practices" throughout your code.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Some companies and projects have also shared their ESLint configs.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] You can also find linting tools for other languages, such as stylelint.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Also known as **version control systems** (VCS), **source code control** is essential for backing work up and working in teams.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] A typical VCS involves having a local version of the code that you make changes to.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] You then "push" changes to a "master" version of the code inside a remote repository stored on a server somewhere.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] There is usually a way of controlling and coordinating what changes are made to the "master" copy of the code, and when, so a team of developers doesn't end up overwriting each other's work all the time.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Git is the source code control system that most people use these days.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] It is primarily accessed via the command line but can be accessed via friendly user interfaces.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] With your code in a git repository, you can push it to your own server instance, or use a hosted source control website such as GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] You can find more information about it at Git and GitHub.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Code formatters are somewhat related to linters, except that rather than point out errors in your code, they usually tend to make sure your code is formatted correctly, according to your style rules, ideally automatically fixing errors that they find.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Prettier is a very popular example of a code formatter, which we'll make use of later on in the module.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Type checkers are tools that help you write more reliable code by checking that your code is using the right types of data in the right places.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] This prevents common classes of bugs such as accessing nonexistent properties, unexpected `undefined`, etc.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] TypeScript is the de facto standard type checker for JavaScript.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] It provides its own type annotation syntax and is somewhat a language in its own right, so we won't be covering it in this module.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] This stage of your web app lifecycle typically allows you to code in either "future code" (such as the latest CSS or JavaScript features that might not have native support in browsers yet) or code using another language entirely, such as TypeScript.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Transformation tools will then generate browser-compatible code for you, to be used in production.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Generally, web development is thought of as three languages: HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, and there are transformation tools for all of these languages.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] The option to write your code in an entirely different language and have it transformed into a web-compatible language.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Post-development tooling ensures that your software makes it to the web and continues to run.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] This includes the deployment processes, testing frameworks, auditing tools, and more.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] This stage of the development process is one that you want the least amount of active interaction with so that once it is configured, it runs mostly automatically, only popping up to say hello if something has gone wrong.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] These generally take the form of a tool that will automatically run tests against your code to make sure it is correct before you go any further (for example, when you attempt to push changes to a GitHub repo).
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] This can include linting, but also more sophisticated procedures like unit tests, where you run part of your code, making sure they behave as they should.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Deployment systems allow you to get your website published, are available for both static and dynamic sites, and commonly tend to work alongside testing systems.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] For example, a typical toolchain will wait for you to push changes to a remote repo, run some tests to see if the changes are OK, and then if the tests pass, automatically deploy your app to a production site.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] GitHub Pages is nicely integrated with GitHub itself and is free for all public repos.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Other services, such as Netlify and Vercel, are also very popular, featuring generous free tier quotas, smooth deployment workflows, and GitHub integration.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] There's certainly an order in which the different tooling types apply in the development lifecycle, but rest assured that you don't *have* to have all of these in place to release a website.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] However, including some of these tools in your process will improve your own development experience and likely improve the overall quality of your code.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] It often takes some time for new developer tools to settle down in their complexity.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] One of the best-known tools, webpack, has a reputation for being overly complicated to work with, but in the latest major release, there was a huge push to simplify common usage so the configuration required is reduced down to an absolute minimum.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] There's definitely no silver bullet that will guarantee success with tools, but as your experience increases you'll find workflows that work *for you* or for your team and their projects.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Once all the kinks in the process are flattened out, your toolchain should be something you can forget about and it *should* just work.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Most tools tend to get written and released in isolation, so although there's almost certainly help available it's never in the same place or format.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] It can therefore be hard to find help with using a tool, or even to choose what tool to use.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] The knowledge about which are the best tools to use is a bit tribal, meaning that if you aren't already in the web community, it is hard to find out exactly which ones to go for!
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] This is one reason we wrote this series of articles, to hopefully provide that first step that is hard to find otherwise.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] When you've chosen a tool to use, the first port of call should be the tool project homepage.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] This could be a full-blown website or it might be a single readme document in a code repository.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] The date-fns docs for example are pretty good, complete, and easy to follow.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Some documentation however can be rather technical and academic and not a good fit for your learning needs.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Instead, you might want to find some dedicated tutorials on getting started with particular types of tools.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] A great starting place is to search websites like CSS Tricks, Dev, freeCodeCamp, and Smashing Magazine, as they're tailored to the web development industry.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Again, you'll probably go through several different tools as you search for the right ones for you, trying them out to see if they make sense, are well-supported, and do what you want them to do.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] This is fine — it is all good for learning, and the road will get smoother as you get more experience.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] That rounds off our gentle introduction to the topic of client-side web tooling, from a high level.
[src:webpack/client-side-tools-overview] Next up we will look at package managers.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] Minification can be distinguished from the more general concept of data compression in that the minified source can be interpreted immediately without the need for a decompression step: the same interpreter can work with both the original as well as with the minified source.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] The goals of minification are not the same as the goals of obfuscation; the former is often intended to be reversed using a pretty printer or unminifier.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] However, to achieve its goals, minification sometimes uses techniques also used by obfuscation; for example, shortening variable names and refactoring the source code.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] When minification uses such techniques, the pretty-printer or unminifier can only fully reverse the minification process if it is supplied details of the transformations done by such techniques.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] If not supplied those details, the reversed source code will contain different variable names and control flow, even though it will have the same functionality as the original source code.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] In 2001 Douglas Crockford introduced JSMin, which removed comments and whitespace from JavaScript code.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] It was followed by YUI Compressor in 2007.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] In 2009, Google opened up its Closure toolkit, including Closure Compiler which contained a source mapping feature together with a Firefox extension called Closure Inspector.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] In 2010, Mihai Bazon introduced UglifyJS, which was superseded by UglifyJS2 in 2012; the rewrite was to allow for source map support.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] From 2017, Alex Lam took over maintenance and development of UglifyJS2, replacing it with UglifyJS3 which unified the CLI with the API.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] In 2018, Terser has been forked from uglify-es and has gained momentum since; in 2020 it outstripped UglifyJS when measured in daily downloads.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] Since late 2018, Terser has recommended the bundler RollupJS.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] A **source map** is a file format that allows software tools for JavaScript to display different code to a user than the code actually executed by the computer.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] For example, to aid in debugging of minified code, by "mapping" this code to the original unminified source code instead.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] The original format was created by Joseph Schorr as part of the Closure Inspector minification project.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] Version 2 and 3 of the format reduced the size of the map files considerably.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] In 2024, source maps were standardized by Ecma International's TC39 technical committee as ECMA-426.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] JavaScript and Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) resources may be minified, preserving their behavior while considerably reducing their file size.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] Libraries available online are capable of minification and optimization to varying degrees.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] Some libraries also merge multiple script files into a single file for client download.
[src:webpack/minification-programming] JavaScript source maps can make code readable and debuggable even after it has been combined and minified.
[src:webpack/module-bundler] A **module bundler** is a software development tool that takes multiple source files and their dependencies (*modules*) and combines them into one or more output files called *bundles*.
[src:webpack/module-bundler] Module bundlers are commonly used in front-end web development to package JavaScript, CSS and other assets for efficient delivery to web browsers.
[src:webpack/module-bundler] Module bundlers typically start from one or more entry points and build a dependency graph of all imported modules before producing the final bundles, often applying optimisations such as minification and tree shaking.
[src:webpack/tree-shaking] It relies on the import and export statements to detect if code modules are exported and imported for use between JavaScript files.
[src:webpack/tree-shaking] In modern JavaScript applications, we use module bundlers (e.g., webpack or Rollup) to automatically remove dead code when bundling multiple JavaScript files into single files.
[src:webpack/tree-shaking] This is important for preparing code that is production ready, for example with clean structures and minimal file size.
[src:webpack/webpack] webpack takes the dependencies and generates a dependency graph allowing web developers to use a modular approach for their web application development purposes.
[src:webpack/webpack] It can be used from the command line or can be configured using a configuration file which is named *webpack.config.js*.
[src:webpack/webpack] This file defines rules, plugins, etc., for a project.
[src:webpack/webpack] webpack provides code on demand using the moniker *code splitting*.
[src:webpack/webpack] Two similar techniques are supported by webpack when it comes to dynamic code splitting.
[src:webpack/webpack] The first and recommended approach is to use the *import()* syntax that conforms to the ECMAScript proposal for dynamic imports.
[src:webpack/webpack] The legacy, webpack-specific approach is to use *require.ensure*.
[src:webpack/webpack] webpack also provides a built-in development server, *webpack-dev-server*, that can be used as an HTTP server for serving files while developing.
[src:webpack/webpack] It also provides the capability to use hot module replacement (HMR), which updates code on a webpage without requiring the developer to reload the page.
